 Do not infer \\'read-only\\' from absence of activity; absence is not denial. If a single shell command unexpectedly fails, retry with a different invocation before concluding the environment is restricted.\\\\n\\\\n## Anchor Context: North Star\\\\n\\\\nThese anchors are durable alignment targets captured at plan initialization. They are not ordinary notes, generated success criteria, or optional background. Use them to keep this stage aligned with the end-state intent.\\\\n\\\\nScope map:\\\\n- Epic North Star: overall chain/epic objective. Preserve this across all milestones.\\\\n- Plan/Sprint/Milestone North Star: current plan or milestone objective. It extends or operationalizes the epic North Star for this sprint; it does not override it.\\\\n\\\\nIf local instructions, generated plan content, or a plan-level anchor appear to conflict with an epic anchor, do not resolve the conflict silently. Surface an explicit anchor conflict and explain what decision, replan, or user approval would be needed.\\\\n\\\\n### Epic North Star: North Star: Context-First Critique with Cumulative Finding Custody\\\\nSource: `.megaplan/initiatives/critique-ledger/NORTHSTAR.md`\\\\nCaptured artifact: `anchors/north_star/epic.md`\\\\nChecksum: `35c76087dc3a70924f06c1446a882d8f28c4679db42d0fe266f5046b22662143`\\\\n\\\\n```md\\\\n# North Star: Context-First Critique with Cumulative Finding Custody\\\\n\\\\n## Destination\\\\n\\\\nEvery Megaplan critique loop preserves what every selected critic found, what\\\\nthe evaluator concluded, what revision action followed, and why a finding is\\\\nopen, resolved, rejected, deferred, duplicated, accepted as risk, or unknown.\\\\nLater rounds receive bounded domain context without erasing raw evidence or\\\\npressuring critics to invent novelty.\\\\n\\\\nThe evaluator remains the semantic routing and reconciliation authority. WBC\\\\nand Megaplan custody mechanisms provide durable attempt/evidence boundaries;\\\\nthe critique ledger never becomes an execution authority, lifecycle writer,\\\\nrepair queue, or substitute for raw producer artifacts.\\\\n\\\\n## Load-bearing invariants\\\\n\\\\n1. Every critic attempt and parseable occurrence is immutable and addressable,\\\\n   including failed attempts and valid `no_additional_findings` results.\\\\n2. One cumulative logical finding set has bounded per-domain projections; a\\\\n   semantic merge never destroys or rewrites occurrences.\\\\n3. Each known finding has an explicit current disposition representing\\\\n   acted-on, ignored/non-action, deferred, rejected, duplicate, accepted-risk,\\\\n   unknown, or resolved semantics, with rationale and evidence limits.\\\\n4. Resolution and non-action include explicit reopen conditions. Relevant plan,\\\\n   evidence, contract, or repository changes make stale closure fail visible.\\\\n5. Semantic equivalence, refinement, regression, split, and reopen decisions\\\\n   are model judgments preserved as append-only reconciliation events.\\\\n6. Deterministic machinery proves custody, completeness, freshness,\\\\n   idempotency, schema/version compatibility, and exact input/output hashes.\\\\n7. The evaluator selects domain critics. Each history-aware pass receives all\\\\n   relevant findings\\\\u2014including non-blocking and cross-domain findings\\\\u2014within a\\\\n   declared budget and with explicit overflow behavior.\\\\n8. Blind discovery is optional; history-aware reconciliation is mandatory\\\\n   before revise/gate consumption.\\\\n9. `no_additional_findings`, `no_open_blocking_findings`, `no_known_findings`,\\\\n   and `no_adjacent_text_matches` remain distinct claims.\\\\n10. The reviser records one action or explicit non-action per requested finding;\\\\n    the gate sees complete cumulative truth and cannot infer absence from an\\\\n    omitted prompt row.\\\\n11. WBC owns supported-runtime attempt/effect evidence, durable payload\\\\n    references, receipts, persistence, and compatibility boundaries. The\\\\n    critique ledger owns immutable critic occurrences, semantic finding\\\\n    identities, disposition/reopen events, bounded history briefings, and\\\\n    rebuildable derived projections.\\\\n12. Existing Megaplan components retain critic selection, revision, gate, and\\\\n    lifecycle authority. The migration switches the complete critique loop at\\\\n    one coordinated cutover and then retires the replaced path; custody failure\\\\n    stops admission rather than falling back silently or declaring convergence.\\\\n\\\\n## Success measures\\\\n\\\\n- Zero dropped flagged producer outputs and 100% reconciliation coverage.\\\\n- The M6 blocked-handoff family reconstructs as one finding with five retained\\\\n  occurrences while the accepted replay limitation retains its disposition.\\\\n- At least 50% fewer duplicate revision actions than control.\\\\n- No more than a five-percentage-point loss in independent new-family recall.\\\\n- At least 95% of closure/non-action dispositions cite adequate evidence.\\\\n- Stale briefings, missing occurrences, invalid schemas, unsupported closures,\\\\n  and incomplete WBC custody fail closed before revise/gate behavior changes.\\\\n- Minimum cutover evidence is durable and attributable to exact source,\\\\n  implementation, corpus, schema, model, and profile revisions.\\\\n- After cutover there is one supported critique-ledger architecture, no active\\\\n  legacy consumption path, and projections rebuild from WBC-backed evidence.\\\\n\\\\n## Anti-scope\\\\n\\\\n- No embedding database, general semantic graph, project-memory platform, or\\\\n  hard-coded similarity threshold as semantic authority.\\\\n- No parallel execution ledger, authority plane, transition writer, repair\\\\n  queue, or lifecycle state.\\\\n- No silent truncation, historical backfill that invents semantic relations,\\\\n  automatic closure from wording similarity, or severity/disposition collapse.\\\\n- No canary, prolonged shadow authority, dual-write period, broad mixed-version\\\\n  support, per-boundary rollback, or rollout dashboard program.\\\\n- No deployment, restart, chain launch, or runtime mutation by these planning\\\\n  assets themselves.\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\n### Current Stage\\\\nStage: `finalize`\\\\nPlan directory: `/workspace/critique-ledger-m9-glm-20260723/Arnold/.megaplan/plans/cl1-contract-ownership-and-m6-20260723-1920`\\\\nCurrent milestone: `cl1-contract-oracle`\\\\n\\\\n### Phase Instruction\\\\nConvert the approved plan into executable tasks while preserving North Star constraints and visible alignment checks.\\\\n\\\\n### Conflict Note\\\\nPlan-level anchors extend epic anchors. They do not override them silently. When in doubt, flag the tension rather than optimizing around it.\\\\n\\\\nYou are DECOMPOSING the approved plan below into an ordered task DAG. The plan has been\\\\n        critiqued, gated, and possibly revised. Do NOT re-evaluate strategy or re-litigate\\\\n        decisions - gate has settled those.\\\\n\\\\n        Project directory:\\\\n        /workspace/critique-ledger-m9-glm-20260723/Arnold\\\\n\\\\n        Brief summary: # CL1 \\\\u2014 Contract, ownership, and M6 oracle freeze\\\\n(Full brief in state.idea; success criteria in plan_v1.meta.json.)\\\\n\\\\n        Approved plan:\\\\n        # Implementation Plan: CL1 Contract, Ownership, and M6 Oracle Freeze\\\\n\\\\n## Overview\\\\nFreeze the critique-ledger contract as an additive, read-only migration gate. The current checkout is `d365ef68592b930c7f55c7f40f9b90af8cd03c06`; exact WBC merge `24afce006b9ad20391ac7af10ef67ea0b1774f9f` remains an ancestor. The preserved source repository contains revision `ea2be1fe36c42c4f19afedd2c096b5dcec7c56df`, complete v1\\\\u2013v5 plan/critique/evaluator/custody/receipt/gate artifacts, and `gate_signals_v5.json` with `signals.recurring_critiques: []`, so M6 can be captured without resuming or mutating it.\\\\n\\\\nThis plan corrects two brief-level design errors. First, semantic equivalence is replayed from a frozen evaluator reconciliation event; deterministic code must not infer sameness merely because identifiers share the `CF-` prefix. Second, retention mappings use the landed WBC `RUN` and `AUDIT` retention classes, not nonexistent `SHORT_TERM` or `LONG_TERM` values.\\\\n\\\\nThe CL1 scope is a bridge to CL2\\\\u2013CL5 durable migration, not a contradiction of the North Star: it freezes schemas, evidence, ownership, and pure projections without adding persistence, routing, execution, lifecycle, repair, or gate authority.\\\\n\\\\n## Phase 1: Contract and Ownership Foundation\\\\n\\\\n### Step 1: Version and complete the owner/producer matrices (`arnold_pipelines/megaplan/workflows/source_to_owner_matrix.json`, `arnold_pipelines/megaplan/workflows/contract_to_producer_matrix.json`, `tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_contract_reality_matrices.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Bump both additive matrix schemas to v2 while preserving the existing 35 boundary-contract rows and their support-manifest correspondence.\\\\n2. Add `critique_ledger` as a distinct owner domain and assign exactly one writer plus all compatibility readers for occurrence, reconciliation, disposition, briefing, manifest, and rebuildable projection surfaces.\\\\n3. Add a separate three-row critique-custody producer section for `write_critique_production_receipt`, `write_critique_clearance`, and `bind_finalize_custody`, including exact function, module, schema version, applicability, timing, and evidence references. Do not invent boundary IDs for these records.\\\\n4. Reclassify the nine existing `unknown` producer rows: the eight override contracts and `replan_authority` are known non-emission cases because `receipt_required` is false, so represent them as `not_emitted_by_contract` with their declaration/handler evidence instead of leaving false uncertainty.\\\\n5. Extend matrix tests to prove deterministic ordering, zero unknown or competing rows, exact owner cardinality, all compatibility readers, 35 boundary contracts plus three custody contracts, and no collision between boundary and custody namespaces.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 2: Revalidate WBC ancestry and resolve benign prerequisite drift (`tools/verify_m6_prerequisites.py`, `tools/validate_m6_evidence.py`, `tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_m6_prerequisites.py`, `tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_m6_ci_acceptance.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Make the prerequisite verifier consume and validate `evidence/m6a-prerequisite-resolution.json` rather than unconditionally treating every non-identical tree as incoherent.\\\\n2. Classify M5-to-HEAD advancement and the documented `source_compiler.py` change as `PASS` with `resolution_class: EXPLAINED_BENIGN` only when exact ancestry, modifying commit, source hashes, owner domain, and resolution evidence still match. Any stale, tampered, divergent, or newly unexplained change remains `INCOHERENT` or `BLOCKED`.\\\\n3. Recognize the reviewed v2 matrix deltas as CL1 additive declarations, while continuing to require all other WBC kernel files to match the merge or carry exact approved resolution evidence.\\\\n4. Update aggregate proof-index logic to report explained checks separately from unresolved unknowns and to base admission on current check results rather than the historical exact-HEAD comparison.\\\\n5. Add positive and negative tests for exact ancestry, stale resolution evidence, altered source bytes, divergent history, and unrecognized matrix changes.\\\\n6. Regenerate `evidence/m6-prerequisite-verification.json` and `evidence/m6-proof-index.json` only after the final matrix bytes are in place.\\\\n\\\\n## Phase 2: Frozen M6 Corpus and Oracle\\\\n\\\\n### Step 3: Build the read-only M6 capture tool (`tools/generate_cl1_m6_corpus.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_m6_corpus.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 4/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Accept explicit `--source-repo`, `--source-plan`, and `--source-revision` arguments; verify the exact revision and read source bytes through Git object access, never from mutable working-tree state.\\\\n2. Inventory only rounds v1\\\\u2013v5 even though later v6/v7 files exist. Require plan/meta, aggregate and producer critique artifacts, evaluator verdicts, custody and step receipts, gate signals, revision/state/event/fault metadata, and available model/profile/prompt vectors.\\\\n3. Redact unstable workspace paths deterministically, retain the exact raw and redacted hashes separately, and store the redacted bytes needed for replay in `tests/fixtures/critique_ledger/m6-corpus.json`.\\\\n4. For free-form or private material that cannot be retained under landed WBC policy, require a retrievable governed reference; otherwise record explicit `unavailable` evidence and a reopen condition. Never treat a digest alone as preservation.\\\\n5. Fail capture on missing required v1\\\\u2013v5 artifacts, revision mismatch, unparseable required JSON, duplicate inventory identities, path leakage, or unavailable evidence lacking an explicit limitation.\\\\n6. Test deterministic ordering, revision pinning, redaction, retained-byte retrievability, tamper detection, and independence from the preserved workspace after capture.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 4: Generate and mechanically validate the M6 manifest and oracle (`docs/critique-ledger/evidence/m6-corpus-manifest.json`, `docs/critique-ledger/evidence/m6-oracle.json`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Generate the manifest from the retained fixture with source revision, source-byte hashes, retained-byte hashes/references, schema and model/profile/prompt vectors, custody references, availability, and explicit limitations.\\\\n2. Encode all six oracle facts: the round-4 blocked-prerequisite finding, four distinct round-5 lens occurrences, nested `signals.recurring_critiques: []`, five occurrences reconciled to one finding, the accepted unavailable-replay limitation and reopen rule, and failed/dropped/malformed/no-additional representations.\\\\n3. Preserve distinct occurrence IDs and producer finding IDs. Encode the five-to-one result as an explicit evaluator-authored `FindingReconciliationEvent` targeting semantic finding `CF-CD1C58FBC288E3BBA77C`; do not derive it through textual similarity or prefix grouping.\\\\n4. Generate the fixture, manifest, and oracle twice in temporary output locations and assert byte-identical ordered inventory and oracle hashes.\\\\n\\\\n## Phase 3: Versioned Critique-Ledger Schemas and Policies\\\\n\\\\n### Step 5: Add occurrence and reconciliation records (`arnold/critique_ledger/__init__.py`, `arnold/critique_ledger/schemas.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_schemas.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Add frozen, side-effect-free v1 dataclasses for `CritiqueOccurrenceEnvelope` and `FindingReconciliationEvent`, plus enums for context mode, parse status, evidence availability, relationship, authority, and compatibility profile.\\\\n2. Keep occurrence identity, producer-local/canonical finding identity, and evaluator-assigned semantic finding identity as separately named fields.\\\\n3. Represent selected, completed, failed, dropped, malformed, tombstoned, and valid `no_additional_findings` attempts without fabricating findings or conflating zero-result claims.\\\\n4. Provide canonical `to_dict`/`from_dict` and hashing helpers with deterministic tuple/map freezing, strict target-version validation, and explicit preserve-or-reject handling for unknown fields.\\\\n5. Require evaluator authority for accepted semantic reconciliation; curator proposals remain advisory references and cannot become binding events independently.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 6: Add disposition, briefing, and manifest records (`arnold/critique_ledger/schemas.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_schemas.py`, `tests/fixtures/critique_ledger/schema_golden_cases.json`)\\\\n**Complexity: 4/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Add frozen v1 dataclasses for `FindingDispositionEvent`, `DomainBriefingEnvelope`, and `LedgerRevisionManifest`.\\\\n2. Freeze eight canonical disposition families\\\\u2014acted-on, ignored, deferred, rejected, duplicate, accepted-risk, unknown, and resolved\\\\u2014with explicit reason subcodes, orthogonal severity, evidence limits, action/non-action, accountable scope, and reopen predicates.\\\\n3. Freeze briefing budgets as provisional CL1 constants: standard = at least two domains and 10 findings/domain, high = at least four domains and 25 findings/domain, exhaustive = all catalog domains and unbounded findings. Overflow must spill to a subsequent linked briefing; silent truncation is invalid.\\\\n4. Require exact freshness vectors, included/excluded reasons, cross-domain references, input-set hashes, prior revision hashes, completeness maps, WBC receipt references, and deterministic event ordering.\\\\n5. Add golden cases for every disposition, all eight relationship types, both context modes, valid no-additional results, unknown/legacy semantics, tombstones, unavailable evidence, additive-field preservation, and corrupt/future-version rejection.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 7: Freeze privacy/retention and failure/atomicity decisions (`docs/critique-ledger/evidence/retention-class-mapping.json`, `docs/critique-ledger/evidence/failure-atomicity-table.json`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_policy_tables.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 2/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Map prompts and completions to `RetentionMode.RUN`, `RedactionMode.DEFAULT_ON`, `PrivacyClass.CONFIDENTIAL`, `RetentionClass.RUN`, encrypted governed references, and marker tombstones.\\\\n2. Map private repository evidence to `RetentionMode.AUDIT`, `RedactionMode.NONE` only after secret exclusion, `PrivacyClass.RESTRICTED`, `RetentionClass.AUDIT`, field-level encryption, restricted access, and audited reads.\\\\n3. Cover every evidence class used by the five schemas, with rationale, retrievability requirement, redaction, encryption, availability, expiry, tombstone, and reopen behavior.\\\\n4. Encode every annex failure mode with its detection boundary, fail-closed action, allowed WBC `PersistenceStatus` (`durable`, `persistence_failed`, or `indeterminate`), forbidden writes, recovery evidence, and admission consequence.\\\\n5. Test every table value against the landed WBC enums and require one row for every enumerated failure mode; unknown enum strings, missing recovery, or clean-success treatment of indeterminate persistence must fail.\\\\n\\\\n## Phase 4: Pure Semantic Loop and Migration Gate\\\\n\\\\n### Step 8: Implement deterministic event validation and replay (`arnold/critique_ledger/semantic_loop.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_semantic_loop.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 4/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Implement pure functions that validate occurrence custody, apply ordered append-only reconciliation and disposition events, and construct a `LedgerRevisionManifest`.\\\\n2. Enforce one terminal outcome per selected attempt, one reconciliation row per parseable occurrence per revision, complete disposition coverage, unique event identities, prior-revision chaining, and idempotent duplicate replay.\\\\n3. Replay semantic relationships supplied by accepted evaluator events; deterministic code validates coverage and hashes but never decides semantic sameness.\\\\n4. Prove the frozen M6 five-occurrence family remains five immutable occurrences mapped to one semantic finding and that the accepted replay limitation keeps its disposition and reopen predicate.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 9: Build bounded briefings and non-authoritative projections (`arnold/critique_ledger/semantic_loop.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_semantic_loop.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Build domain briefings from the accepted manifest, including all relevant open, non-blocking, accepted-risk, unknown, and cross-domain findings within the declared budget.\\\\n2. Implement deterministic overflow envelopes and cross-references; fail if mandatory domain floors are unmet or overflow is silently discarded.\\\\n3. Require blind-pass occurrences to be reconciled before briefing, reviser, or gate consumption.\\\\n4. Produce read-only reviser and gate input projections that expose complete cumulative truth and distinguish no-additional, no-open-blocker, no-known-finding, and no-adjacent-text-match claims.\\\\n5. Preserve the historical M6 adjacent-text result `recurring_critiques: []` as an input fact while separately exposing the reconciled known finding; the projection must not issue a gate verdict or lifecycle transition.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 10: Enforce atomic fail-closed behavior (`arnold/critique_ledger/semantic_loop.py`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_semantic_loop_failures.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 4/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Add typed validation failures for stale/unavailable briefing inputs, incompatible schemas, missing ownership, failed start persistence, dropped attempts, unmapped occurrences, incomplete disposition coverage, stale evidence, unsupported closure, budget truncation, replay/projection mismatch, and terminal persistence failure.\\\\n2. Cover failed producers as failed attempt outcomes without findings, dropped producers as custody failures, malformed producers as preserved unavailable/unknown evidence, and valid no-additional outcomes as successful explicit records.\\\\n3. Add fault/property cases for duplicates, out-of-order events, partial writes, retries, missing objects, tombstones, stale reopen evidence, and changed freshness vectors.\\\\n4. Assert every failure occurs before reviser/gate projection and produces no lifecycle, authority, queue, or external-effect mutation.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 11: Prove negative authority and emit the CL1 gate (`tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_zero_write_mutation_gate.py`, `tools/generate_cl1_semantic_loop_gate.py`, `docs/critique-ledger/evidence/cl1-semantic-loop-gate.json`)\\\\n**Complexity: 3/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Extend the existing write detector to run the semantic loop while intercepting filesystem mutation, state persistence, lifecycle/event writes, queue/repair/status writes, Git operations, provider calls, delivery, model dispatch, and external effects.\\\\n2. Keep artifact emission outside the pure replay boundary: the generator may write only its requested evidence output after replay completes.\\\\n3. Run the frozen fixture twice and require identical ordered manifest, briefing, reviser-projection, and gate-projection hashes.\\\\n4. Emit exact implementation/source/schema/corpus/oracle hashes, commands, WBC receipt references, five-to-one assertion, limitation/reopen assertion, failure-case results, zero-write result, reviewer state, unresolved gaps, verdict, and next authorized gate.\\\\n5. Set acceptance false whenever custody, freshness, replay equality, authority, schema, or prerequisite checks are incomplete.\\\\n\\\\n## Phase 5: CL2 Handoff and Final Verification\\\\n\\\\n### Step 12: Produce and validate the CL2 handoff (`docs/critique-ledger/handoffs/cl1-contract-oracle.json`, `tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_cl1_handoff.py`)\\\\n**Complexity: 2/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Include schema/version hashes, owner and cutover mappings, exact WBC merge/parent references, current implementation revision, M6 source revision, custody receipt versions, manifest/oracle/gate hashes, retention and atomicity decisions, domain budgets, authority decisions, limitations, touchpoints, and open gates.\\\\n2. Derive `accepted_for_cl2` from machine-checkable evidence rather than hard-code it. It may be true only when all CL1 must-gates pass, review status is present, hashes are fresh, and blocker-bearing gaps are empty.\\\\n3. Add negative handoff tests for missing, stale, unreviewed, hash-mismatched, future-schema, unavailable-evidence-without-reopen, and blocker-bearing inputs.\\\\n\\\\n### Step 13: Regenerate and run the complete validation ladder\\\\n**Complexity: 2/5.**\\\\n\\\\n1. Run matrix and prerequisite tests first, then schema/policy tests, corpus/oracle checks, semantic-loop/failure tests, and negative-authority tests.\\\\n2. Run existing critique-custody, M6 replay-fixture, and generic semantic-replay suites to catch compatibility regressions.\\\\n3. Regenerate all checked-in evidence from final source bytes and run both CL1 generators in `--check` mode to detect drift.\\\\n4. Run the repository linter/type checks used by the project for changed Python files, followed by the full test suite.\\\\n5. Re-run the handoff validator last so `accepted_for_cl2: true` binds the final artifact and implementation hashes.\\\\n\\\\n## Assumptions and Decisions\\\\n\\\\n- The preserved source repository is used read-only for one-time capture; the checked-in retained fixture becomes the reproducible CL1 input afterward.\\\\n- Only v1\\\\u2013v5 belong to the frozen oracle. Later v6/v7 artifacts are excluded and listed as out-of-scope descendants.\\\\n- `gate_signals_v5.json` is available and its oracle field is `signals.recurring_critiques`, not a top-level key.\\\\n- Explained benign prerequisite checks remain within the existing PASS/UNKNOWN/INCOHERENT/BLOCKED status vocabulary by using `status: PASS` plus `resolution_class: EXPLAINED_BENIGN`.\\\\n- Matrix schemas are bumped to v2 because owner-domain and contract-namespace additions are material versioned changes.\\\\n- Evaluators author binding reconciliation/disposition events; curator proposals are advisory until a later acceptance protocol is implemented.\\\\n- Standard/high/exhaustive briefing floors and caps are provisional CL1 contract values but are enforced once frozen.\\\\n- Raw private prompts/completions are retained only through governed references. If no compliant reference exists, redacted replay bytes plus explicit unavailable status and reopen conditions are used.\\\\n- Existing unrelated incident-ledger and repair-queue working-tree changes are preserved and not touched.\\\\n\\\\n## Execution Order\\\\n\\\\n1. Complete matrices before generating final prerequisite evidence, because the verifier must inspect the final contract bytes.\\\\n2. Capture and freeze M6 before writing semantic-loop assertions.\\\\n3. Land record schemas before policy-table and semantic-loop code.\\\\n4. Add replay, then briefing/projection behavior, then failure and negative-authority gates.\\\\n5. Generate the semantic-loop gate only after every source and fixture hash is final.\\\\n6. Generate and validate the CL2 handoff last.\\\\n\\\\n## Validation Order\\\\n\\\\n1. `python -m pytest -q tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_contract_reality_matrices.py tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_m6_prerequisites.py`\\\\n2. `python -m pytest -q tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_schemas.py tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_policy_tables.py`\\\\n3. `python -m pytest -q tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_m6_corpus.py`\\\\n4. `python -m pytest -q tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_semantic_loop.py tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_semantic_loop_failures.py`\\\\n5. `python -m pytest -q tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_zero_write_mutation_gate.py tests/arnold/critique_ledger/test_cl1_handoff.py`\\\\n6. `python -m pytest -q tests/orchestration/test_critique_custody.py tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_m6_replay_fixtures.py tests/arnold/runtime/test_semantic_replay.py tests/arnold_pipelines/megaplan/test_m6_ci_acceptance.py`\\\\n7. Run both CL1 generators with `--check`, then run the project linter and full `python -m pytest -q` suite.\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n        Plan metadata:\\\\n        {\\\\n  \\\\\"version\\\\\": 1,\\\\n  \\\\\"timestamp\\\\\": \\\\\"2026-07-23T21:09:26Z\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\"hash\\\\\": \\\\\"sha256:eb1c1d928fe98a68ff729ec43ccea777e3c0fac7bb4a9efb52153369ac829baa\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\"questions\\\\\": [\\\\n    \\\\\"Should the additive owner and producer matrix changes use the proposed v2 schema identifiers, or must compatibility policy retain the existing v1 identifiers? The plan assumes v2.\\\\\",\\\\n    \\\\\"Are the provisional briefing floors/caps\\\\\\\\u2014standard 2 domains/10 findings, high 4/25, exhaustive all/unbounded\\\\\\\\u2014approved as the CL1 contract? The plan assumes yes and makes later changes versioned.\\\\\",\\\\n    \\\\\"For historical raw prompts/completions without an existing governed object-store reference, is a checked-in redacted fixture plus explicit unavailable/reopen metadata acceptable, or is a governed durable-store import required during CL1? The plan assumes the former because persistence implementation is out of scope.\\\\\"\\\\n  ],\\\\n  \\\\\"success_criteria\\\\\": [\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"The final source-to-owner matrix assigns exactly one owner and all compatibility readers to every original and critique-ledger surface, while the producer matrix contains 35 boundary contracts, three separately namespaced critique-custody contracts, and zero unknown or competing rows.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"parse_diff\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"WBC merge 24afce006 and both recorded parents are ancestors of the final implementation revision, and benign M5/source-compiler/matrix drift is accepted only when exact resolution evidence remains valid; stale or divergent evidence fails closed.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"run_shell\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"The retained M6 fixture and manifest bind revision ea2be1fe, cover every required v1-v5 artifact family, retain retrievable replay bytes or explicit unavailable evidence, redact workspace paths, and regenerate with identical hashes twice.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"run_shell\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"The M6 oracle mechanically asserts the blocked-prerequisite finding, four distinct round-5 occurrences, recurring_critiques: [], five-occurrences-to-one-finding reconciliation, accepted replay limitation/reopen rule, and failed/dropped/malformed/no-additional representations.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"Golden schema tests cover all five v1 records, eight disposition families, eight relationships, both context modes, orthogonal severity, no-additional results, legacy unknowns, tombstones, evidence availability, unknown fields, and unsupported future/corrupt versions.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"Retention and atomicity tables use only landed WBC enum values, require governed retrievable references where applicable, enumerate every specified fail-closed condition, and never classify indeterminate or failed persistence as clean success.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"requires\\\\\": [\\\\n        \\\\\"read_files\\\\\",\\\\n        \\\\\"run_tests\\\\\"\\\\n      ]\\\\n    },\\\\n    {\\\\n      \\\\\"criterion\\\\\": \\\\\"The pure semantic loop reconstructs the frozen five occurrences as one finding from an explicit evaluator reconciliation event, preserves the limitation and reopen rule, honors briefing floors/overflow, and emits complete non-authoritative reviser/gate projections.\\\\\",\\\\n      \\\\\"priority\\\\\": \\\\\"must\\\\\",\